english:
  title: Edict on the Investiture of the Crown Prince
  author: Choe Wi-seon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the twenty-second year of Chunghee, in the month of February, on the ninth day, the King proclaimed:

    Since ancient times, Heaven has brought forth the people and established a ruler to govern all affairs with sincerity and care. The eldest son succeeds as heir—a law that endures through a hundred generations without change. This is the eternal principle, arising not from private affection but from the natural order.

    I, though unworthy, stand at the head of all people and aspire to establish perpetual peace and harmony. The state's foundation grows firm through righteous establishment; the glory of our descendants shines through the wisdom we transmit to them. Yet I have held back, as one gathers the pearls upon a robe, waiting for the worthy who would bear this great charge. Now Heaven's blessing has descended—my eldest son has been graced with brilliance and wisdom. Already proven in both talent and reputation, it is fitting that he should inherit the throne and ascend to glory.

    Hark, my son! Your nature runs deep and broad as the boundless waters, your bearing stands noble and luminous as the mountain peaks. Though at an age when children delight in play and games, you have drawn near to the aged and virtuous, eager to hear the Way. The songs of our people rise in unison; the gaze of all officials converges as one. Therefore, you shall ascend to the seat beside the Purple Palace and stand upon the highest steps of the Green Chamber. We have chosen an auspicious day and bestow this proclamation with special grace.

    We hereby dispatch the Minister of the Gate and Recorder of Deeds, Wang Ch'ung-chi, as chief envoy, and the Right Minister of Personnel and Counselor of State, Park Sung-kyul, as deputy envoy. They shall bear the imperial seal and, with full ceremony, proclaim you Crown Prince.

    Behold! When the Han Emperor ascended at seven years of age, it became a tale of beauty. When the Sage King consulted with his attendants thrice daily, he demonstrated devotion to virtue. Let these examples guide you: strive to follow their noble deeds. The higher your station, the more vigilant you must be—let only righteous counsel be your teacher. Let virtue and goodness shine forth; neglect neither your duty to nurture the realm nor to oversee its governance. Hold my teachings sacred in your heart, and surely all will flourish.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Purple Palace' (紫殿) refers to the royal court; the 'Green Chamber' (靑墻) represents the highest ranks of government office.
    - The reference to Emperor Wu of Han ascending at age seven and the Sage King consulting advisors thrice daily evokes classical precedents meant to inspire the young prince toward virtue and diligent governance.
    - This edict follows the formal structure of royal proclamations, blending Confucian ideals of filial succession with appeals to celestial mandate and ancestral example.
